[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$4-15 per active member per month (depends on engagement frequency, channel mix, model choice, RAG depth, multi-system integration depth, and human care-coordinator escalation overhead)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m David is 67. Six weeks ago, in the cafeteria of his daughter's office building where he had stopped to bring her lunch, he had what he later learned was a transient ischemic attack. His left hand stopped cooperating with the sandwich it was holding, his speech slurred for about ninety seconds, and then everything came back. His daughter, who is a nurse, took one look at him and put him in her car and drove him to the emergency department. The ED ran a workup, admitted him for observation, did an MRI that showed a small old infarct his cardiologist had never mentioned, started him on a new antiplatelet, ordered carotid imaging which was abnormal, consulted neurology, consulted vascular surgery, did a transthoracic echocardiogram which suggested possible left atrial enlargement, ordered an outpatient transesophageal echocardiogram, ordered a thirty-day cardiac event monitor, suggested an outpatient sleep study to rule out sleep apnea contributing to his atrial enlargement, restarted a statin he had quietly stopped two years ago, adjusted his blood pressure medications, scheduled outpatient follow-up with neurology, vascular surgery, cardiology, and his primary care physician, scheduled a follow-up MRI in three months, recommended a stroke-prevention nutrition consult, and discharged him on a Friday afternoon with a stack of paper that included six new appointment cards, three new prescriptions, two patient-education brochures, and a discharge summary that ran to nine pages.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m David, who is a retired industrial-equipment salesman with a high school education and roughly average health literacy, sat in the passenger seat of his daughter's car holding the stack of paper and tried to figure out what was going on. The discharge nurse had been kind. The discharge nurse had been moving fast, because David's bed was needed and there were two more patients in the ED waiting for admission. The discharge nurse had said the words "transient ischemic attack" and "vascular surgery" and "cardiology" and "thirty-day monitor" and "sleep study" and "follow-up imaging" and "carotid stenosis" and "statin compliance is really important now" in a continuous five-minute monologue. David had nodded. David's daughter had taken notes on her phone. David got home at 4:47 PM and spent the rest of the weekend trying to read the discharge summary, which contained eleven medical abbreviations he did not recognize and described tests whose names he could not pronounce.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What happened over the next six weeks is not unusual.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m David called the neurology office on Monday morning to confirm his appointment. The neurology office said his appointment had been scheduled for the wrong week and the next available was eleven weeks out. David called vascular surgery; vascular surgery said they had no record of a referral and asked David to have his PCP send one. David called his PCP; the PCP's office said the PCP had not received the discharge summary and asked David to bring a copy when he came in. David's outpatient TEE got scheduled, but the cardiology practice that did the TEE was not the same cardiology practice that David's regular cardiologist worked at, so the results went to a different chart and David's regular cardiologist did not see them for about three weeks. The thirty-day cardiac monitor arrived in the mail with a thirty-page instruction booklet and a phone number for a call center that was perpetually busy; David wore the monitor for nine days, took it off because it was uncomfortable, and never put it back on. The sleep study referral was sent to a sleep-medicine practice that was not in-network with David's Medicare Advantage plan; David did not know this, attended the appointment, and got a bill for $1,847 in the mail four weeks later. The new antiplatelet prescription required a prior authorization that the discharging hospitalist had not initiated; David's pharmacy gave him a five-day supply and told him to call his doctor; David called his PCP, who had not seen the discharge summary, who told him to call neurology, who could not see him for eleven weeks. David ran out of the antiplatelet on day eight. He did not take it for the next eighteen days.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The follow-up MRI was scheduled for September. The vascular surgery consult was scheduled for August. The cardiology follow-up was scheduled for July. The PCP follow-up happened in June, at which point the PCP, looking at David sitting in the exam room and trying to assemble what had happened, said something gentle and almost embarrassed, which was that this was not the way the system was supposed to work but that David had clearly been falling through cracks and that they were going to start over and rebuild a plan together. David's daughter, who had taken time off from work to be at the visit because she had stopped trusting that her father could navigate the system alone, began to cry. The PCP, who is a good doctor with a good heart and a forty-five-minute slot for an annual visit that this had become, did her best.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This story, in some version, happens millions of times a year in the United States. <!-- TODO: verify; care-transition failures including post-discharge medication errors, missed follow-up appointments, and fragmented multi-specialist care are documented in studies including those by Forster et al. 2003, Kripalani et al. 2007, and follow-on work; specific figures vary by population and methodology --> Care coordination, when it works, is the work of holding a patient's care across providers, across institutions, across time, and across the gaps between them. Care coordination, when it does not work, is exactly what happened to David: appointments that don't get made, referrals that don't connect, prescriptions that don't get filled, results that don't reach the right chart, prior authorizations that don't get initiated, in-network status that doesn't get verified, and a patient at the center of all of it trying to assemble a coherent picture from nine pages of discharge paperwork written for clinicians.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The clinical and economic stakes are not subtle. Care-coordination failures contribute to readmissions, to preventable adverse events, to medication errors, to missed cancer screenings, to delayed treatment of progressive conditions, to surprise bills, and to the slow erosion of patient trust in the system as a whole. <!-- TODO: verify; the relationship between care-coordination failures and downstream adverse outcomes is documented in studies including the AHRQ National Healthcare Quality and Disparities Reports and the Institute of Medicine's Crossing the Quality Chasm; specific figures vary --> The patients most affected are predictably the patients with the most complex care: older adults with multiple chronic conditions, patients with recent hospitalizations, patients with cancer in active treatment, patients with serious mental illness navigating fragmented behavioral health, patients with rare diseases coordinating across multiple specialists in different cities, pediatric patients with complex chronic conditions, and patients with the least social and financial resources to compensate for the system's gaps.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The healthcare system has long known this is a problem and has long had a partial answer in the form of human care coordinators (sometimes called care managers, case managers, navigators, or coordinators depending on the institution and the role). Care coordinators do exactly what David needed: they call the offices, they verify the in-network status, they reconcile the discharge summary, they shepherd the prior authorizations, they make sure the test results land in the right chart, they translate the medical jargon, and they hold the longitudinal map of where the patient is in the journey. The labor model for care coordination, as for nurse care management, does not scale to the population that would benefit. Care coordinators are typically reserved for the highest-risk members in capitated populations, for cancer patients with active treatment, for patients in specific disease-management programs, and for the patients with the most catastrophic-cost trajectories. <!-- TODO: verify; care-coordination programs typically reach single-digit percentages of plan populations, focused on highest-acuity members; specific reach figures vary by payer, program, and condition --> David, who had a TIA without stroke, who has Medicare Advantage but not the highest-tier care-management program, who is not in active cancer treatment, who is not enrolled in a chronic-disease-management program, was a member of the broad middle of patients with complex care needs who do not qualify for human care coordination. David got the system as it works for the broad middle, which is to say, David got the stack of paper.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generation of digital care-coordination products tried to address this with patient portals and appointment-tracker apps. The patient could log into a portal, see their upcoming appointments, message their care team, view some lab results, and request medication refills. The clinical evidence for these tools is mixed; they helped patients who would have done well anyway, and reached the broad middle inconsistently. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for patient-portal use including its association with improved care outcomes is documented in studies including those by Goldzweig et al. 2013, Otte-Trojel et al. 2014, and ongoing meta-analyses; specific figures vary by population and condition --> The fundamental limit of the patient-portal approach is that it asks the patient to do the coordination work themselves: to read the test results, to schedule the follow-up, to navigate the prior authorization, to verify the in-network status, to track the referrals. The patients who can do this are mostly the patients who do not need much help; the patients who cannot are mostly the patients who need help most.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What changed, around 2023, is that conversational AI got good enough to do some of the care-coordination work itself. A patient who would not log into the portal will, sometimes, respond to a chat that says "Hi David, I see you were discharged yesterday with five new appointments. Want me to walk through them and make sure everything's set up?" The chat is connected to the institution's scheduling, EHR, referral, prior-auth, and benefits systems. The chat can verify the in-network status, can confirm or correct the appointment dates, can identify the missing referral, can flag the prior authorization that has not been initiated, can translate the discharge summary into language the patient can understand, can answer the questions the patient was too embarrassed to ask the discharge nurse, and can know when to escalate to a human care coordinator. The chat is not a person. The chat is, in the right product design, a tool that extends the care-coordination workforce to reach the broad middle of complex-care patients who would otherwise be left to assemble the picture from a stack of paper.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about that system. The care coordination assistant is the conversational AI use case where the architectural patterns from the previous chapter 11 recipes converge into a single multi-system orchestration product, and where several specific patterns enter the picture: multi-system integration as architectural primitive, longitudinal episode tracking across providers and institutions, structured handoff to human care coordinators for the cases that need them, intent-aware routing across the chapter's other bots (scheduling, refills, intake, benefits, triage, chronic coaching, mental health), and a delicate calibration of automation versus human-coordinator support that is harder to get right than it looks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the bot that helps a patient navigate complex care across multiple providers, multiple institutions, and multiple care episodes, with appointment coordination, referral tracking, results reconciliation, prior-authorization shepherding, in-network verification, discharge-instruction translation, between-visit question handling, and structured escalation to human care coordinators when the situation requires.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a primary scheduling bot. Recipe 11.2 covers single-encounter scheduling. The care coordination assistant orchestrates across many encounters, frequently delegating individual scheduling actions to the scheduling bot.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a benefits navigator. Recipe 11.5 covers benefits questions in depth. The care coordination assistant calls into benefits-navigation pathways when an insurance, eligibility, or in-network question surfaces.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a triage bot. Recipe 11.6 covers acute-symptom triage. The care coordination assistant routes acute symptoms to triage and resumes coordination work afterward.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a chronic disease coach. Recipe 11.7 covers longitudinal disease-specific coaching. The two products often coexist for multi-chronic-condition patients; the chronic coach focuses on disease management, the coordination assistant focuses on system navigation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a mental health support bot. Recipe 11.8 covers behavioral-health support. The coordination assistant escalates mental-health concerns to the appropriate pathway.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a substitute for the human care coordinator. The bot extends the care-coordination workforce; it does not replace it. The patients with the most complex needs still get the human coordinator. The bot handles the broad middle, the night-and-weekend questions, the after-discharge confusion, the routine follow-up reminders, and the appointment-and-referral mechanics that are high-volume and lower-judgment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-size-fits-all product. The coordination needs of a post-discharge cardiac patient are different from the coordination needs of an oncology patient in active treatment, which are different from the coordination needs of a patient with a newly diagnosed rare disease coordinating across out-of-state specialists. Most institutions deploy the coordination assistant with a focus on specific high-volume care-transition use cases (post-discharge, post-ED, oncology, transplant, complex pediatric, frequent-utilizer) and expand from there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a regulatory afterthought. Patient-facing care-coordination software, particularly when it provides direct guidance about care plans, medications, or follow-up, sits on or close to the FDA Software-as-a-Medical-Device line in some configurations. <!-- TODO: verify; the FDA's regulatory positioning of patient-facing care-coordination software depends on the specific functionality, the recommendations the software produces, and the institution's claims; the regulatory landscape continues to evolve --> The institutional regulatory team is involved from architectural design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in quarters, not sprints, because the multi-system integration work is inherently multi-quarter and the institutional change-management around the human-coordinator role is multi-quarter as well.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the bot's value is not in any individual answer it gives. The value is in the orchestration: the consistency of follow-up after a discharge, the catch when an appointment was scheduled for the wrong week, the surfacing of a missing referral before it becomes an eleven-week wait, the translation of nine pages of discharge instructions into a coherent plan, the warm handoff to a human coordinator when the situation needs one. A coordination assistant evaluated on per-conversation engagement metrics will be optimized for the wrong thing. A coordination assistant evaluated on care-transition success rates, on appointment-completion rates, on prior-authorization-initiation rates, on follow-up-imaging-completion rates, on readmission rates, and on patient-reported coordination experience is being evaluated correctly, and the architectural decisions follow from there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Multi-System Conversational Care Coordination Across Providers, Episodes, and Care Transitions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Resisted Digital Tools For Twenty Years
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical workflow, has been a phone-and-fax-and-clinic-centric problem for several decades. The reason is structural. Care coordination requires holding, simultaneously, what the patient understands about their care, what the discharging clinical team intended, what each downstream provider needs in order to act, what each system's scheduling and referral and prior-authorization processes require, what the patient's insurance covers and where, and what the patient's social and logistical realities allow. The work is most of the cognitive lift. Producing the actual phone call to the office is the easy part once the model is in place.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing care coordinators do, when they do this well, is hold a longitudinal episode model of the patient: which care episode is the patient in, what are the open follow-up items, who has acted on what, where are the bottlenecks, what is at risk, and what is the next thing that has to happen. The model is rebuilt every time a coordinator picks up the patient's case, partly from the chart and partly from a phone call to the patient. Holding the model across institutions, across providers in different EHRs, across the gaps between systems, is the part that does not scale to the labor model the country has.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first generation of digital care-coordination products, roughly the early 2000s through the late 2010s, tried to solve this with patient portals. The patient logged in, saw appointments, messaged the team, viewed results. The clinical evidence for these tools as care-coordination interventions was, broadly, that they helped patients who would have done well anyway and did not reach the broad middle of complex-care patients. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for patient-portal use as a care-coordination intervention is mixed, with the strongest effects observed for patients with already-favorable digital-engagement profiles; specific figures vary --> The fundamental problem these products had was that the coordination work was still asked of the patient. The portal was a tool for the patient to do the work themselves.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second generation, roughly the late 2010s through the early 2020s, layered care-coordinator-side workflow tools on top of the patient-facing portal. Care coordinators got case-management dashboards with longitudinal task lists, alerting on overdue items, integrated patient communication, and (in some platforms) cross-EHR data integration. The clinical evidence for these tools when paired with adequate care-coordinator staffing was meaningful; the operational problem was again that care-coordinator staffing did not scale to the population that would benefit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape is large language models that can carry on coherent multi-system orchestration conversations with patients. A coordination assistant, deployed with careful institutional governance, can carry the longitudinal-episode model the human coordinator would carry (it has the chart, it has the discharge summary, it has the appointment list, it has the referral status, it has the prior-auth status, it has the in-network status, it has the patient's stated preferences and concerns), can engage in the kinds of focused, specific, timely conversations the human coordinator would have, can call into the institution's scheduling, referral, prior-auth, and benefits systems through structured tool use, can translate clinician-language into patient-language and back, and can know when the situation has exceeded what bot mediation should handle and route to a human coordinator. The LLM is not a coordinator. The LLM is, in the right product design, a tool that lets the care-coordination workflow operate at population scale, with the human coordinator workforce focused where their judgment is most needed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "patient logs into portal to do the work themselves" to "bot orchestrates across the systems, surfaces bottlenecks, drives action, and escalates when human judgment is required." The bot's value is concentrated in three places: the multi-system orchestration (turning a discharge stack of paper into a coherent followed-through plan), the early-warning escalation (catching coordination breakdowns before they become eleven-week waits or surprise bills), and the operational reach (extending the care-coordinator workforce from the highest-acuity members to the broad middle of complex-care patients).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (active care episodes, recent encounters, active referrals, scheduled appointments, open follow-up items, active prior authorizations, current medications, recent discharge summaries, the patient's stated preferences and concerns, conversation history), access to a structured set of integrations into the institution's scheduling, referral, prior-authorization, benefits, and EHR systems, and a careful set of tools for orchestrating across them and escalating to human coordinators when the situation requires.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is not one conversation. It is a stream of conversational episodes, sometimes initiated by the patient (post-discharge confusion, between-visit questions, results just received, surprise bill in the mail), sometimes initiated by the bot per a care-episode protocol (post-discharge follow-up at 24 hours, 72 hours, and 7 days), sometimes triggered by a system event (appointment scheduling failure, prior-authorization denial, in-network status change, lab result requiring follow-up).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The bot's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-episode initiation and onboarding.** A care episode is initiated by a clinical event: hospital discharge, ED discharge with follow-up requirements, new diagnosis requiring multi-specialist coordination, oncology treatment plan initiation, transplant evaluation, complex pediatric diagnosis. The episode-initiation step instantiates the coordination plan from the institution's protocol library, captures the open follow-up items from the discharge summary or care plan, links the relevant referrals and orders, and schedules the bot's initial outreach.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Post-event outreach.** Within hours of the initiating event, the bot reaches out to the patient. The first conversation introduces the bot, confirms the patient's preferred channel and language, walks through the open follow-up items in plain language, confirms which appointments are already scheduled and which need to be, identifies any obvious gaps (missing referrals, prior authorizations not initiated, prescriptions requiring authorization), and offers to act on the gaps within scope or to escalate them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Appointment and referral coordination.** The bot tracks scheduled appointments, confirms them with the patient, identifies scheduling conflicts and rescheduling needs, verifies in-network status against the patient's coverage, surfaces appointments scheduled for the wrong week or with the wrong provider, identifies missing referrals (a follow-up requested by the discharging team that the receiving practice has no record of), and either initiates the corrective action through the institution's scheduling and referral systems or flags the issue for the care team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Results and follow-up reconciliation.** The bot tracks ordered tests and procedures, confirms completion, identifies orders that have not been completed (the thirty-day cardiac monitor that was returned after nine days; the follow-up MRI that was scheduled and missed), reconciles results that landed in the wrong chart with the appropriate clinical team, and communicates results to the patient in plain language when the institution's policy allows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prior authorization shepherding.** The bot tracks the prior-authorization status for new prescriptions, follow-up imaging, and elective procedures, identifies when a prior authorization has not been initiated by the discharging team, communicates the status to the patient ("your antiplatelet needs prior authorization, which the hospital should have started; I'm checking on it now"), initiates corrective action through the institution's prior-auth workflow, and escalates to a human coordinator when the prior-auth path is non-trivial.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **In-network verification.** The bot verifies, before the patient walks into a referred appointment, that the referred provider is in-network with the patient's coverage. Out-of-network referrals are flagged before the appointment, with options presented to the patient (in-network alternatives, single-case agreement, balance-billing implications). This is the surprise-bill prevention work that the patient was supposed to do themselves and almost never can.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Discharge-instruction translation and questions.** The bot translates discharge instructions, after-visit summaries, and care plans into language the patient can understand. The bot answers questions about medications, follow-up requirements, what to watch for, and what was actually decided in a visit the patient did not fully follow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Between-encounter handling of arising issues.** The bot handles the questions that arise between encounters: confused about a medication, not sure which provider to call about which symptom, uncertain whether a side effect is normal, unsure if a missed appointment was important. The bot answers within scope and routes outside scope (acute symptoms to triage; mental-health concerns to behavioral-health pathway; benefits questions to benefits navigator; chronic-condition-specific concerns to chronic coach where applicable).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-coordinator handoff.** When the situation exceeds what bot mediation should handle, the bot warm-hands-off to a human care coordinator. The handoff includes the conversation transcript, the relevant longitudinal-episode context, the specific reason for escalation, and the patient's preferred contact method. The human coordinator picks up where the bot left off rather than starting over.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team reporting and care-plan-deviation flagging.** The bot generates structured reports for the care team: weekly digests of episode status, alert events for time-sensitive issues, monthly summaries of the patient's coordination experience, and care-plan-deviation flags for situations where the patient's actual journey is diverging from the planned journey.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome tracking.** The bot's deployment is evaluated against measurable outcomes: appointment-completion rate, follow-up-imaging completion rate, prior-authorization-initiation rate, surprise-bill rate, 30-day readmission rate, patient-reported coordination experience, and time-to-completion for key milestones in the care journey.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive approach would be to take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, paste in some institutional content, and expect it to coordinate care. This breaks in several specific ways.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no view of the patient's actual longitudinal episode.** Without integration into the institution's scheduling, referral, prior-auth, benefits, and EHR systems, the LLM can only respond to what the patient says. A coordinator that cannot see what the patient cannot see (the missing referral, the wrong-week appointment, the not-yet-initiated prior auth) is not a coordinator. The multi-system integration is the architectural primitive that distinguishes the assistant from a chatbot.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of care-episode protocols.** Care coordination is not free-form. Each episode type (post-discharge, post-ED, oncology, transplant, etc.) has structured protocols specifying what should happen when. Without the protocol as input, the LLM invents follow-up plans that may not align with the institution's standard of care. The protocol library is owned by clinical leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model hallucinates appointment, referral, and benefit information.** Without strict grounding in the institution's actual systems, the LLM produces plausible-sounding statements ("your appointment with cardiology is on July 15th at 2 PM") that may not correspond to reality. The grounding-against-source-of-truth discipline is non-negotiable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has clinical-administrative arithmetic problems.** Calculations like "the patient was discharged 9 days ago, the post-discharge follow-up was supposed to happen by day 7, so it's now 2 days overdue" are arithmetic on structured inputs. The LLM does this poorly. Deterministic episode-tracking tools handle the time math.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when bot mediation should stop.** A patient with a complex coordination question, a patient with frustration mounting toward distress, a patient with a clinical concern that is more than coordination, a patient with a benefits dispute that the bot's tools cannot resolve: each is a moment to escalate to a human coordinator. The escalation logic is encoded explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of in-network verification.** Verifying in-network status requires calling a real eligibility system with specific provider-and-payer parameters and getting a structured response. The LLM does not do this; the eligibility integration does.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications for coordination conversations.** The conversations contain PHI. They sometimes surface insurance-coverage information protected under different regulatory frameworks. They sometimes intersect with social-determinants-of-health concerns, with mental-health concerns, with substance-use concerns, and with specially-protected categories of health information.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of staying within scope.** Patients in coordination conversations frequently bring up adjacent concerns: clinical questions, benefits questions, refill questions, scheduling questions for non-coordinated visits. The bot answers within scope, routes outside scope to the appropriate sibling service (recipes 11.1 through 11.8), and does not pretend to be a clinician, a benefits expert, or a one-stop shop for the entire chapter.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of care-coordinator workflow.** When the bot escalates, the human coordinator on the receiving end has a workflow with case management software, alert queues, and case-load constraints. Escalations that ignore the coordinator-side workflow erode the coordinator's trust and produce a system that the coordinators stop using.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of patient frustration.** Care-coordination conversations are often happening with patients who are frustrated, scared, or angry, sometimes appropriately so (the system has failed them in specific ways). The bot's tone, pacing, and acknowledgment of the patient's experience matter. A bot that responds to legitimate frustration with cheerful platitudes is a bot that gets opted out of within weeks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Assistant Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation. The care coordination assistant adds eight structural commitments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-system integration as architectural primitive.** The assistant's value is integration. Scheduling system, referral system, prior-auth system, benefits/eligibility system, EHR (FHIR), pharmacy, lab, imaging, and the institution's case-management system all participate. Each integration is a managed contract with specific authentication, error handling, and rate limits.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-episode tracking as durable state.** The episode is the central abstraction. An episode has a type (post-discharge, post-ED, oncology treatment, transplant evaluation, complex pediatric, frequent-utilizer, etc.), a start date, a list of open follow-up items with target dates, a list of completed items, a current status, and an active protocol. The episode is updated every time a relevant event occurs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordination-protocol library with clinical-leadership ownership.** Each episode type has a protocol specifying expected follow-up items, target time windows, escalation criteria, and out-of-bounds conditions. The library is owned by the appropriate clinical leadership (hospital medicine for post-discharge, ED leadership for post-ED, oncology leadership for cancer episodes, transplant leadership for transplant episodes) and is reviewed annually.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-bot intent routing.** The assistant is the chapter's most likely first contact for many patients with complex needs. It must classify intents and route across the chapter's other bots cleanly: scheduling concerns to recipe 11.2, refills to recipe 11.3, intake to recipe 11.4, benefits to recipe 11.5, triage to recipe 11.6, chronic coaching to recipe 11.7, mental-health to recipe 11.8. The routing is visible to the patient and the conversation context follows the patient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Human-coordinator handoff as first-class capability.** The bot is not the entire care-coordination workforce; it is the front line. The handoff to a human coordinator is a designed product feature, not an afterthought. The human coordinator's case-management workflow integrates with the bot's session.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **In-network verification as architectural primitive.** Surprise bills are one of the central failure modes the assistant is designed to prevent. In-network verification before referral or self-scheduled appointments is run automatically and surfaced to the patient, with alternatives offered when out-of-network status is detected.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-plan-deviation detection.** The assistant compares the patient's actual journey to the planned journey from the protocol and flags deviations: missed follow-up, overdue prior auth, wrong-week appointment, non-completed test, missing referral. Detection is deterministic per the protocol; the LLM does not invent the deviation list.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome correlation with downstream events.** The assistant's deployment is tied to measurable outcomes: appointment-completion rate, prior-auth-initiation rate, follow-up-imaging-completion rate, surprise-bill rate, readmission rate, patient-reported experience. The pipeline is multi-quarter post-launch work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous recipes: identity-assurance, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes coordination specifically harder than the previous patient-facing use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-system integration is the single largest engineering investment.** Most of the assistant's value is in the integrations. A coordination assistant without scheduling integration cannot confirm appointments. Without referral integration cannot detect missing referrals. Without prior-auth integration cannot shepherd authorizations. Without eligibility integration cannot verify in-network status. Each integration is a multi-week to multi-quarter project, and the institutional API maturity varies wildly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The institutional case-management software defines the human-coordinator workflow.** The bot has to fit into the case-management software the institution already uses, not the other way around. Case-management software vendors include Epic Healthy Planet, Salesforce Health Cloud, Innovaccer, Welkin, and others; each has its own integration story.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The bot makes the gaps in the institution's processes visible at scale.** Most institutions' care-transition processes have gaps that the human-coordinator workforce papers over. The bot does not paper over gaps; it surfaces them, often at high volume. The first three months of deployment frequently feel like the bot has revealed how broken the institution's processes are, when in fact the bot has just made the existing brokenness measurable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-coordinator workforce reaction is not always positive.** Coordinators sometimes worry the bot will replace them; sometimes worry the bot will make their work harder by escalating low-value cases; sometimes worry the bot will damage their relationships with patients. Change-management with the coordinator workforce is part of the deployment, not an afterthought.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-frustration handling is a specific design competence.** Coordination conversations are often happening at moments of patient frustration. The bot's tone, the bot's acknowledgment of system failure where it has occurred, the bot's escalation when frustration mounts, are all calibrated. A bot that responds to "this is the third time I've called about this" with "I'm sorry to hear that, can I help schedule your appointment?" is a bot that ends the conversation badly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-EHR data integration is uneven.** Most patients in complex-care journeys are coordinated across multiple EHRs (the discharging hospital, the receiving specialist, the PCP, the imaging center, the pharmacy). FHIR interoperability has improved substantially over the last several years but remains incomplete; the assistant's data picture is often patchier than the human coordinator's data picture, which the human coordinator constructs by phone.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prior-authorization automation is the highest-leverage feature.** A meaningful fraction of post-discharge medication non-adherence is driven by prior-authorization friction. <!-- TODO: verify; the relationship between prior-authorization friction and medication non-adherence is documented in pharmacy and adherence literature; specific figures vary --> The bot's prior-auth shepherding work is one of the highest-impact features by patient-experience and clinical-outcome measures.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Surprise-bill prevention is the highest-leverage trust feature.** A patient who gets a surprise bill after the bot scheduled the appointment is a patient who never trusts the bot again. The in-network verification before any scheduling action, with explicit acknowledgment of the in-network status to the patient, is non-negotiable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cultural and linguistic considerations are not optional.** The patients with the most complex care-coordination needs are often the patients with the least access to and comfort with the system, with corresponding implications for language, literacy, cultural-context, and digital-engagement comfort.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinants-of-health context is constant.** Patients without transportation cannot make appointments at the imaging center across town. Patients without childcare cannot make weekday appointments. Patients with unstable housing cannot reliably receive mailed prior-auth-decision letters. The bot's recommendations have to account for the patient's actual logistical reality, with care-navigation handoffs to social-services pathways where the institution has them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The coordination job decomposes differently across institutional types.** Hospital systems coordinate post-discharge journeys. Payers coordinate benefits and care-management programs. Integrated delivery networks coordinate both. Specialty centers (oncology, transplant, rare disease) coordinate around their specific clinical pathway. The bot's design and integrations vary by institutional type.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR-based care-plan and follow-up tracking has matured.** The FHIR CarePlan, ServiceRequest, Appointment, and Task resources provide a structured representation of care-coordination state that maps cleanly to the assistant's episode model. <!-- TODO: verify; FHIR R4 and R5 specifications include CarePlan, Goal, ServiceRequest, Appointment, Task, and related resources used for care-coordination representation; specific resource-level usage varies by EHR vendor and institution --> Institutions whose EHR vendors expose these resources via FHIR APIs have substantially less integration work than institutions on older interfaces.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-coordination interoperability standards are advancing.** Frameworks including the ONC's Da Vinci project, the Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement (TEFCA), and CMS's interoperability rules have improved cross-institution data sharing. <!-- TODO: verify; ONC interoperability rules including the 21st Century Cures Act final rule, CMS interoperability rules, the Da Vinci project, and TEFCA implementation continue to evolve; specific compliance dates and reach vary --> The assistant's cross-institution data picture is improving but remains uneven.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prior-authorization automation has improved substantially.** APIs from clearinghouses (Availity, Surescripts, Change Healthcare, others) and from specific payers have made automated prior-auth submission feasible for many medication and imaging categories. <!-- TODO: verify; prior-authorization automation is uneven by payer and category; CMS rules including the 2024 prior-authorization final rule have set requirements for electronic prior-authorization implementation that continue to phase in --> The assistant's prior-auth shepherding can drive automated submission for the categories with mature APIs and structured-handoff for the others.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Eligibility and benefits APIs are widely available.** Real-time eligibility verification (270/271 transactions) and provider-network verification are widely supported by clearinghouses and individual payers. The assistant's in-network verification is feasible at scale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle multi-system orchestration well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from previous chapter 11 recipes maps cleanly to coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve episodes, retrieve appointments, retrieve referrals, retrieve prior-auth status, verify eligibility, schedule actions through sibling services, and propose escalations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid bot-plus-coordinator deployment is the dominant production pattern.** Most major deployments run a hybrid model: bot for the broad middle of complex-care patients, with human coordinators for high-acuity cases, escalation cases, and patient-requested human contact. The economics work because the bot handles the high-volume routine work while the coordinator focuses where their judgment is most needed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is mixed but trending positive.** Studies of digital-plus-human care-coordination programs have shown reductions in 30-day readmissions, improvements in appointment-completion rates, and improvements in patient-reported coordination experience for engaged participants, with effect magnitude varying by program design, condition, and population. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for digital-plus-human care-coordination programs is documented in studies of post-discharge transitional-care programs, oncology navigation programs, and complex-care management programs; specific outcome figures vary --> The strongest evidence is for transitional-care programs in the first 30 days post-discharge, which is also the highest-volume coordination use case.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity and disparity considerations are a major area of attention.** Patients with the greatest coordination needs are often the patients with the least access to digital tools, the most language and literacy barriers, and the most social-determinant burdens. Per-cohort monitoring is essential.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some segments.** Several care-coordination platform vendors operate at scale (Honest Health Group, Cohere Health, ZeOmega, Salesforce Health Cloud, Innovaccer, others). Most major institutions run a hybrid: build a thin coordination-orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for specific capabilities (case-management software, prior-auth automation, eligibility-verification), and integrate with the institution's care-management, EHR, and specialty-program infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
